From: KTLYST Strategy <assafkip@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] adversarial-review: honor scope filter, calibrate approval, dampen post-round-1 churn

The adversarial-review prompt currently optimizes for "find something." When a
caller invokes it more than once on the same diff, or against a small contract
slice that is already correct, the prompt's bias toward findings drives the
model to manufacture concerns outside the change surface. In an iterative DSSE
workflow this loops indefinitely: each new "finding" gets patched, which
regenerates the diff, which generates new "findings."

This patch makes three small changes:

1. Adds a <scope_filter> block. If the user_focus contains a "Scope filter" or
   "Contract slice" line (e.g. a JSON list of allowed paths), the model treats
   it as a hard constraint and explicitly marks anything outside it as
   out-of-contract instead of proposing a patch.

2. Reframes the approval clause in <structured_output_contract>. Today's
   wording ("only if you cannot support any substantive adversarial finding")
   reads as "approval is the failure case." New wording explicitly licenses
   honest scope-bounded approval.

3. Adds one line to <calibration_rules>: when a scope filter or contract slice
   is present and the slice has already been reviewed once, raise the bar.
   Iteration is not a license to expand the contract.

The change is purely additive to the prompt template. Existing call sites that
do not pass a scope filter behave identically.

---
 prompts/adversarial-review.md | 14 +++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/prompts/adversarial-review.md b/prompts/adversarial-review.md
index 0000000..0000001 100644
--- a/prompts/adversarial-review.md
+++ b/prompts/adversarial-review.md
@@ -8,6 +8,16 @@ Target: {{TARGET_LABEL}}
 User focus: {{USER_FOCUS}}
 </task>

+<scope_filter>
+The user focus may include a "Scope filter" line listing allowed paths (e.g. a JSON array or glob list) and/or a "Contract slice" directive.
+If a scope filter is present, treat it as a hard constraint:
+- Limit findings to defects inside the listed paths.
+- A finding that requires changes outside the scope is OUT OF CONTRACT for this review. Mark it explicitly as out-of-scope in the body and do not propose a patch for it.
+- Do not flag pre-existing patterns in unchanged code, even if you would normally flag them.
+- Do not raise edge cases that would require new follow-up issues unless they are defects in the diff itself.
+- If you have no defect inside the contract slice after honest review, return `approve`. Honest scope-bounded approval is the right answer; manufacturing findings to satisfy adversarial framing is not.
+</scope_filter>
+
 <operating_stance>
 Default to skepticism.
 Assume the change can fail in subtle, high-cost, or user-visible ways until the evidence says otherwise.
@@ -49,7 +59,7 @@ Every finding must include:
 Return only valid JSON matching the provided schema.
 Keep the output compact and specific.
 Use `needs-attention` if there is any material risk worth blocking on.
-Use `approve` only if you cannot support any substantive adversarial finding from the provided context.
+Use `approve` if you cannot support any substantive adversarial finding inside the contract slice. Approval is the correct verdict when the diff is sound within its declared scope; do not invent findings to avoid approving.
 Every finding must include:
 - the affected file
 - `line_start` and `line_end`
@@ -69,6 +79,7 @@ Be aggressive, but stay grounded.
 Prefer one strong finding over several weak ones.
 Do not dilute serious issues with filler.
 If the change looks safe, say so directly and return no findings.
+If a scope filter or contract slice is present and you have already reviewed this slice once, raise the bar for additional findings: only report defects with a concrete reproduction path, not edge cases that would require speculation. Iteration is not a license to expand the contract.
 </calibration_rules>

 <final_check>
--
